node.text: I stained my shirt. A sole pepperoni slid down a river of its own grease and glided ever so softly along the fabric of my white Hanes tagless tee. It took three bounces before leaving a mark resembling Orion’s belt across my chest. Problem was, I had 48 hours in New York City and one clean t-shirt. Thank goodness the pepperoni stopped short of my cargo pants. It was hardly 11:00am and you could find me standing at a high top, alone, with a thin napkin tucked deep into the collar of a stained t-shirt, on the brink of another bite. I’d seen this picture a hundred times on Instagram. The rare, thick square slice breaking the New York promise of thin pie cut za. Prince Street Pizza manufactures delicious pepperoni grease pools in a tiny, low lit hole in the wall, and I’d gladly trade them another t-shirt to eat this slice again. When you order at the counter, they pop it in the oven to crisp it up. It comes out with the perfect crunch but still has the stick-to-the-roof-of-your-mouth chew to it. It’s a light layer of sauce paired with heavy cheese. I’d recommend that you keep it to one slice. The grease pools are no joke. #isthatthepizzaman? #pizzaman #pizza #infatuation #forkyeah #chicago #newyork #chicagogram #food #eeeeeats #chicagofoodie #chicagofoodauthority #chicagofood #chicagopizza

It's no joke that the Pizzaman has taken a serious hiatus from posting, and for that I apologize. What's also no joke is this za from Ballaro in Highwood. They offer just three pizzas, a clear sign of confidence in what they put out. Between the four cheese, house made sausage, and a fancy ass duck prosciutto pizza which I readily passed on, I went with the sausage. This pizza is great. Ballaro went bold with the pie-cut, and although being more of the thin and crispy variety, the crust had just enough chew to manage a futon-style fold. The Pizzaman is not a big basil guy, so naturally I picked that off. However, disguised as the onion-looking item, the pickled fennel tickled the taste buds and danced gleefully atop the cheese as if they were deckhands on the Santa Maria. The new kid on the block in a competitive Highwood restaurant scene, Ballaro has a lot to prove.
Fancy guy out on the town.

node.text: It was Saturday night and the Pizzaman had a pizza plan. Pequods on Clybourne followed by Zootopia, a truly heartwarming cinematic adventure. Nothing could break my spirits, except for a two and a half hour wait. Although I had my heart set on the 'Quods, Zootopia wasn't gonna watch itself. Sometimes pulling a last minute pizza audible can lead to something great. The Pizzaman packed up his Hyundai and headed west on an adventure. Three miles and four Prince songs later, I walked right in to Root's. The West Town staple was busy, but not two and a half hour wait busy. Root's has been on my list for years. The self proclaimed "Quad Cities Style Pizza" still kind of confuses me. The waitress explained that this style of pizza "is round and has the cheese on top." Puzzled, I ordered a Daisy Cutter, mozzarella sticks and settled in. The mozz sticks were homemade and outrageous. Potentially the best I've ever had and easily the biggest. On to the za. Pizzaman fans know that I'm a sauce guy. I judge a pizza largely by the quality of the sauce and Root's has a deep red, thin sauce with a little bit of heat on the back end. I ordered a sausage pizza. They grind and spice their meat in house and hand toss the dough. They spread the sausage in small crumbles under the cheese so you get it in every single bite. It. Was. Awesome. With a lively bar, solid apps and relatively cheap za, Root's was the perfect audible.

So this is what they call the matza pizza. It's 1 part hilarious and 2 parts disgusting. I would first like to Passover some knowledge. The matza pizza is a far cry from what the Torah intended. Moses magically and amazingly parted the Red Sea in two and lead the Jewish people on a 40 year exodus through the deserts of Ancient Egypt into freedom. It's hard to imagine that his first move post-slavery was to squat in his tent and fix himself a nice matza pizza...But I guess we'll never know! The 21st century Jewish Men of Pizza strive to continue this tradition. I like to spread my tomato sauce with a gap in the middle so it appears that  I, in honor of Moses, am also parting the Red Sea.

Shiver me timbers, it's National Deep Dish Pizza Day! So batten down the hatches and climb aboard this clipper as we celebrate the only way I know how. All hands on deck matey's! This is the Pizzaman Pirate Edition. 
For those of ye scallywags without yer sea legs, this man-o-war is a slice of Pequods, the crown jewel of Chicago Deep. Aye, this is just an old Seadog's opinion. If ye so choose to side with Lou's, might as well climb down Jacob's ladder and hornswaggle yer way to the poop deck! Girodano's? You must be three sheet's to the wind and loaded to the gunwalls! Pizanos? I'd rather walk the plank and spend eternity in Davy Jones' Locker! Those scallywags couldn't sauce a pizza if Blackbeard himself was on their tail! The perfect deep dish must have a thick red layer of sauce and the crust to boot. Scouring the Seven Seas o' Pizza is no easy task, but somebody's gotta do it.
Small.

Scroll through the Pizzaman Archives, and you'll find a rather detailed and eccentric post about my frozen pizza preference. I'm a Tombstone guy with little to no room for negotiation. But when Homerun Inn opened up a location on Belmont and Sheffield, I just had to go. Although I'm on Team Tombstone, the Homerun Inn frozen variety is arguably the most popular brand. It's a super unique taste with very little sauce, like three pepperoni's TOPS and a sour dough-esque crust that for some reason tastes better when it's a tad undercooked. #BakeAt325. I fully expected the restaurant to serve up a similar style pizza, but they could not be more different. It's a thick thin-crust like Pie Eyed or Piero's, it rocks a totally saucy sauce and goes nuts on the toppings. Plus their square-cut slices are tiny and you feel like a pizza beast working through that za #TwoBiteSlice. Plus, the crust is so flaky that it almost didn't show up #nice. It's a tasty pizza and cheap on the spectrum, but don't go there expecting to get a similar za to the frozen. If frozen pizza tasted like this, I'd be a big time Homerun Inn guy.

node.text: I drove to Wisconsin tonight to get pizza. Wells Brothers is a 95-year-old pizza tavern 20 minutes north of the Mars Cheese Castle in downtown Racine. We were lucky a friendly couple scooted over for us and we snatched two seats at the bar. Even at 5:30pm on a Tuesday night it was packed wall to wall with locals. They have a deal every Tuesday. For $20 you can get a large pizza, fries and six Miller Lite shorties. But quickly after sitting down, our new friend Jim the Bartender filled us in on a poorly kept secret. They sell cans of Hamm's beer for just 95 cents every single day, one cent for every year they've been in business. A few Hamm's later I considered moving to Racine and I hadn't even tried the pizza yet. Students of the Pizzaman know that I appreciate a square cut, thin crust, tavern style za and I didn't drive to Racine,WI for a mediocre experience. Wells Brothers is a less salty Nick and Vito's with a Barnaby's-esque cornmeal crust. They grind their sausage in house and recommend you order the pizza well-done. It is so thin and so easy to smash. We ordered two pizzas and had to stop ourselves from finishing both. We concluded the meal with a 1-for-1 Slices Draft for the leftovers just before a complimentary Andes chocolate mint.

I don't get my pizzas delivered. It's a trust thing. It all started when I was just a pup, an arrogant young Pizzaman. It was late summer 1998 and I sat there waiting. The tight curls of my Jew-fro danced in the wind as I rolled down the back seat window. I watched as he walked out of Piero's (See Pizzaman Archives picture 65) carefully cradling two large pizzas. I was having friends over for dinner. He opened the back door, gently placed the pizzas atop my lap and waited as I struggled to secure the cargo. "Hold it straight." He closed the door and the heat of the pizza box began to burn through my AYSO shorts. Halfway home and I couldn't take it anymore. I slid the pizzas off my lap and on to the empty seat to my left. Little did I know that I had just ruined our dinner. One mile and five minutes later we pulled into the garage, grabbed the pizzas, and walked them into the house. The natural slant of the backseat set off an avalanche of cheese and toppings, so much so that my friends thought I ordered a half cheese, half sauce-only pizza. After a proper scolding, I learned my lesson the hard way. But I've come a long way. I've since delivered pizzas for two separate establishments and pride myself on 0 new cheese avalanches. As a retired pizza delivery man, turned Pizzaman, I still find it hard to trust others to deliver a level-pizza. But I'm working on it. For now, I'll stick to picking up my own pizzas.

I hope you are all enjoying National Pizza Day. No work, no school, dancing in the streets and what not. Usually on this day you can find a disheveled version of the Pizzaman knee-deep in tomato sauce and up to my neck in leftover crust. Anywho, today is the Super Bowl of Pizza and in the spirit of celebration, I thought I'd share with you my recent super bowl pizza spread. Pictured above are the only "squares" that should matter on Super Bowl Sunday. The first quarter alone I hit four squares and by halftime I hit another six. Anything is possible when you have pizza this fantastic. The trifecta pictured above features your classic Barnaby's pepperoni, the epitome of #orangenapkin pizza. The middle za represents pizza in it's purest form. Folding a middle slice of Barnaby's cheese pizza is a true Pizzaman past time. Lastly, we have our sausage and mushroom two-topper #fancyass. This meat and veggie hybrid was a party favorite and proved it's worth as the first za finished.

The Pizzaman's phone always has sauce on it, except for today. The Country Fried Chicken Pizza at Revolution Brewing uses sausage gravy as its base. This za is then topped with B-Dubbs style boneless wings tossed in hot sauce and finished with a sunny side egg. However this pizza is a slightly exclusive, weekends only brunch option.

Eataly could quite possibly be my favorite way to kill an hour or two in the entire city. If you're unfamiliar with Eataly, it's a gourmet Italian super store specializing in weight gain and intoxication. It took me four trips to Eataly before I actually sat down and tried their pizza. At peak times, it's often an unbearable experience, but if you finagle yourself free around like 2pm on a Tuesday, go. Go alone. Walk around. Drink some beer and eat some pizza. Get a cup 'o joe and risotto. Or some wine and cheese if that's more your fancy #pinkieup. The bars upstairs urge you to grab a glass and stroll through the store. There's a lot to see, don't panic, find the restaurant you're in the mood for. Since I'm the Pizzaman, let's talk pizza. Behind Spacca Napoli and Pizzeria de Nella, Eataly stacks up third on my list of best Neapolitan za's in Chicago. The sauce is tangy and sweet and actually incredible. The crust has the perfect bubbled burn. Although the flavor might have been the best yet, the crust lacked a certain crunch. It was thicker and chewier than I hoped for. Also, questionable pepperoni placement. Super clumpy 'roni at times.

Current situation. It's my birthday. Nothin' like a pizza party.  #whatelsewouldyouexpect #pizza #pizzaman #chicagopizza #chicagofood #chicagofoodauthority #infatuationchi #EEEEEats #everythingerica #bucktown #eater #chicagomag

node.text:
Dante's in Logan square was the second half of my #SlicesOnlySunday. I didn't like it and I'm sorry for this #NotSoRaven review. It was easily the greasiest slice of pizza I've had in Chicago. I've conveniently placed my post-dabbing, greasy napkins next to the slice as evidence. It's a big slice and fights back on the fold. After a few attempts, I eventually completed a successful fold. But the end of the slice quickly flopped and the cheese and toppings came rushing down onto my lap like a downhill slip-n-slide #pizzapants. I ended up taking a few bites of the remaining za with a fork and knife and you shouldn't have to do that with a simple pepperoni thin crust slice. Dante's is on the bottom floor of a small two-story brick building in an unassuming neighborhood. It has a dark and hellish vibe, scary pictures of Devils on the wall and the cashier has a face tattoo and wouldn't look me in the eye.  It's a drive to get there for me and it's not particularly a known Chicago pizza destination. So why did I go here? I had it a few years ago and it was delicious! It was a memorable slice and I don't know what happened. I'm deeply disappointed. 
#dantes #pizza #pizzaman #chicagopizza #chicagofood #chicagofoodauthority #infatuationchi #EEEEEats #everythingerica #logansquare #eater #chicagomag

Santullo's is my first stop on a #SlicesOnlySunday Pizzaman adventure. Just two storefronts down from Piece, Santullo's often reaps the benefit of hungry pizza fiends unwilling to wait an hour for a table. They offer a quick, big $4 slice. The crust cracks like a whip and folds like a futon. It's not quite orange napkin pizza but when you fold and flip, there is a little grease run off. The slice maintains an honorable crunch throughout which makes the chewy pillow-like crust a splendid surprise. The Pizzaman is definitely a Santullo's Fantullo. 
#santullos #pizza #pizzaman #chicagopizza #chicagofood #chicagofoodauthority #infatuationchi #EEEEEats #everythingerica #bucktown #eater #chicagomag

Believe it or not, the Pizzaman packaged up half of this pied piper and popped it in the fridge for later use. This thin 'n' crispy square-cut secret is only well-known in the Pizzaman archives. Washington Gardens has officially completed a rare feat, a hat trick of Pizzaman pizzagrams. I invite you to dig deep and discover an in depth description of this za in pictures #35 and #57. This post, however, will follow it into another life, an often cold and dark life. A life as "The Leftovers." It's so easy to mess up leftovers and pizza this good deserves a proper reheat. An easy way ruin your #lefties is to keep it in the original cardboard box. A quick #TupperwareTransfer keeps your precious cargo fresh. Don't screw it up, use Tups. When your ready to heat up the leftie za, you have a few options. The microwave is the easiest and the most disgusting. It melts the cheese, softens the crust and the sauce never warms up. If you can spare more than one minute of your night, use the toaster oven. It equally cooks the slice and brings back the crisp, however you do risk a burnt crust. For those of you looking to get wild and make a night of it, reheat your za on the stove. It's a game changer if you do it right. Put a slice or two on a pan over low heat, splash some water on the sides of the pan and cover it for five minutes.

node.text: As the Pizzaman, I try to venture out and find the best pizzas around Chicago. That was until I found this fancy lady in the frozen foods section. I heeled my cart, stared blankly into the glass freezer and pulled out my phone. "Hey. I don't think I can make it out tonight." And suddenly I was on my way home. I don't eat frozen pizza often, but when I do, I prefer Tombstone. The sauce is actually perfect. It tastes exactly like the sauce packets in the pizza Lunchables. Circa 2002, 6th Grade Pizzaman was sucking sauce packets dry in the lunchroom. Anywho, there is one problem with Tombstone: they often skim big time on the cheese and tops. Nothing a packet of #shreddedmozz can't fix. Four hundred degrees and 19 minutes later, I opted for a standard eight slice pie-cut. The packaging advises to wait five minutes before you eat and yada yada yada, my mouth is really burnt today. I recommend pairing this Tombstone with a nice red Gatorade.

The end of a slice is always an emotional moment. The crust stares back at you as a reminder of what once was: A full-bodied, pie-cut slice, slender in width, draped in some #fancyass Italian cheese and finished with spicy salami and truffle oil. It's a #fivebiteslice but if you crack the crust and fold, three bites should get it done. Careful though. The crust is folded and stuffed with ricotta. Ricotta be kidding me. It's divine. For the first time I can remember, I was happy to reach the end of a slice. #pizza #pizzaman #chicago #chicagopizza #chicagofood #chicagofoodauthority #everythingerica #infatuationchi #eater #eeeeeats #dolce

The burnt yellow crust, the chunky tomato sauce and the crunch. Oh the crunch, it was unmistakable. I knew this pizza as soon as it showed its face. Bartoli's is owned by the grandson of the founder of Gino's East. It's merely a twin. A delicious twin. #yes #thatsitalianbeefonmypizza #pizza #pizzaman #chicago #chicagopizza #deepdish #chicagofood #chicagofoodauthority #everythingerica #eeeeeats #eater #infatuationchi

Forgive me for what I'm about to write. I just didn't care for this pizza. If you scroll through the Pizzaman archives, you'll see that I've been to Homeslice twice before and truly enjoyed the experience. Crunchy crust, tangy sauce, a classic combo. Both times I played it safe and went with a pepperoni/sausage or something simple. This time I thought I'd try something different and ordered one of their specialty pizzas...they simply tried too hard. Homeslice calls this one the "Funky McChicken"...😐. A regretful, deplorable mistake. It starts with a cream cheese base, something no pizza should ever start with. Next comes the chicken. Homeslice seemingly went to Jewel,  ordered a pound of week-old Boars Head deli-sliced meat, and topped my pizza with it. Don't put that on my pizza. Thinly sliced meat run through an oven at 425 degrees is going to come out dry. Yet somehow the bacon that followed was thick cut and chewy. Bacon on pizza must be extra crispy. Jalapeños, onions and garlic round this winner out. I actually left pizza on the table and didn't bother to bring it home, and I'm the Pizzaman! If you're at Homeslice, order a normal pizza.

node.text: Two slices later and I feel like I'm sinking. Sinking slowly into the crack of an unforgiving couch. I badly need a napkin. There's pizza sauce on my shoulder. Its dark in here. I need to get up. If only it didn't feel like I was wearing a full body Velcro suit. Is this what it feels like after people work out? Please. Just somebody please help me off this couch.  One. Two. Three. No. Everyone else on this couch fell asleep. The sounds of snoring drowned out only by football. Victims of the Dish, the deepest dish. A dish so deep it is a work of Art. A holy matrimony of sauce and cheese. Pepperoni, oh sweet pepperoni. For only pepperoni, you are my pepperonly.

Talk about a pizza joint that deserves some good buzz #Rirruto. Pizzeria de Nella on Fullerton was half empty at 8pm on a Saturday #notFull-erton #skeptical. 
The Pizzaman could've turned around. He could've walked right out, slinking into the night without a sound. But the Pizzaman honored his reservation! The slow walk to the table provided some clarity and confidence that he had made the right decision. The pizzas were being skillfully placed into the open, wood-fired oven. Warm crunchy bread, oil and parmesan quickly arrived. The menu was deep, the waiter equally knowledgeable. Three Peroni's, please. And some more bread. We'll start with the gnocchi. Yes I want pizza. We'll have the Diavola. Three Peroni's, please. Oh my god is that ours. Wow. Spicy pepperoni. Fold it. Jesus. It's like burnt. But not burnt. Excuse me. One more Diavola. Three Peroni's, please.

It was my first taste of white pizza, a slice I saw at most pizza joints in the Big Apple. Generally not a big basil guy, so I enjoyed the pep sausage a smidgen more. #foldedlikeafuton #pizza #pizzaman #newyork #newyorkcity #nyc #bleeckerstreetpizza #foodporn #EEEEEats #everythingerica

The Pizzaman just had a lovely, long Labor Day weekend enjoying the Big Apple. New York is huge and strange and unique. They also have pizza, and it's practically on any given corner. Three nights and four pizzas later, it's time to come home to Chicago. For if I stay here any longer, I think I might actually turn in to a pizza. 
Although the availability of slices in Manhattan is vast, we travelled to Brooklyn for a special Neapolitan za. Roberta's puts out a similar pizza to Chicago's Spacca Napoli. It's light and airy with a crust freckled with burns. Sweet San Marzano tomato sauce topped with mozzarella and caciocavallo, a mild cheese similar to provolone. It hit the spot.

Stay tuned. Plenty more pizza to post.

There are certain things that come with being the Pizzaman. There's the Good: the consistent curiosity to find, eat and post the best and newest pizza Chicago has to offer. There's the Bad: the multiples of sauce stained clothing and a bare to the bones refrigerator with only the remains of last nights fix. And then there's the Ugly: Chicago is a city recognized for its food, and admired for its pizza. It's a city full of curious eaters and strong opinions. Because of this, the Pizzaman is consistently asked "What's the best?" or "Deep or thin." However, recently, and almost daily, I've been asked "Have you ever been to Blaze?" Chicago offers a deep and unique selection of pizza. And that's why this specific question simply gets me all Blazed and confused. But I'll answer it...of course I've been to Blaze. 
Blaze is the Chipotle of pizza. It's a build-your-own pizza concept centered on a quick cooked za served crispy. And it's good. But it's not a destination. It's not a night out or an evening of entertainment. It's exactly what it markets itself as. A quick, delicious meal.

node.text: Sitting outside @parlorchicago on a warm Friday night with a cold beer is the #trendiest thing you can do right now. Their patio is a big party, a #pizzaparty if you will. People come for the drinks and the atmosphere and it's just a plus that they serve pizza. It's all 10" thin crust, all specialty za's. "Umm can I just have a pepperoni pizza" "No, you can't but I can bring a Hawaiian pizza with #housemade coconut cheese, #housemade spiced ham and delicious pineapple." These trendy specialty pizza places are hit or miss but Parlor seems to have figured it out. The top right pizza is a Gyro pizza with tzaziki, cucumbers and tomato and they nailed it. #pizza #pizzaman #chicagopizza #chicagothincrust #chicagofood #EEEEEats #thatsafancyasspicture #parlorpizza #chicago #westloop

node.text: It's a pizza pot pie. And it's super popular. Chicago Pizza and Oven Grinder in Lincoln Park is consistently packed. So much so that I had to go on a Monday at 530pm to ensure a short wait. So, I guess that makes this a #tbt. Once you get seated, the atmosphere is dark, the booths are tiny and the pizza pot pie is ridiculous. You only get two options: sausage or vegetarian. The "sausage" is a legit bolognese with exactly two big roasted and uncut button mushrooms. The pizza dough is some of the best I've had in Chicago. The vegetarian uses a more traditional pizza sauce plus the shrooms. Can't go wrong either way. They bake these pie zas to order so it's going to take at least a two beer wait, or approximately 40 minutes. That'll give you time to hit the ATM across the street, because #Surpise, it's #CashOnly. #chicagopizzaandovengrinder  #chicagopizza #chicago #chicagofood #pizzapotpie #beers #EEEEEats #eatpizza #pizzaman #pizza

node.text: Alexander's Pizza, Eagle River, WI. Five hours and 290 miles later, I am back home.  This is the pizza that started it all for me. Maybe it's the drive up, the anticipation. Maybe it's the wait, a year-long crave. Maybe it's all the memories, the moments. Or maybe it's just good fucking pizza. The best. It's what I compare it to and nothing is comparable. Picture a 10 year old kid with an unstoppable Jew fro sitting on the top bunk in a 90 degree cabin. In my lap is a life changing moment. A large, sour dough crust, tangy sauce covered in softball sized pepperoni all blanketed by well-done mozzarella. An unstoppable moment in the evolution of the Pizzaman.

It was that moment we all regret. That slow waitress walk. She has my food. There it is. Is that mine? That's not my pizza. She gets closer. Is that really my pizza? Yeah, I guess it's my pizza. 
I wasn't even sure why I ordered it, really. I tried to be impressive and cultured...fancy if you will. A burrata and arugula za that looked like a salad flatbread. It actually turned out to be fairly good, not my favorite, but the wood fired crust had a perfect burn and the slight bitterness of the burrata cheese was a nice touch. The Pizzaman also went back to his roots and settled in for a few slices of pepperoni and garlic za. Overall average. #pizza #pizzaman #chicago #chicagopizza #chicagofood #eeeeeats #woodfiredpizza

😀:"Hey Pizzaman, what's your favorite deep dish?" 🍕😎:"Pequods or Art." 😧:"What? No Lou's?" 🍕😁:"yeah, no Lou's." Above is a conversation I seem to have once a day, every day guaranteed. Let me start off with this. Last night's Lou's was purchased with a $25 off coupon from my roommate. The Pizzaman isn't about to turn down discounted za so here is your long awaited Lou Malnati's Pizzaman review: it's just okay. 
If you call yourself a fan of the Pizzaman, you are well aware that Lou's has been left absent thus far. Due to its undeniable popularity, there have been calls from the  highest mountain tops and the lowest valleys for a Lou's pizza pic. I've even received calls for resignation due to my outstanding belief that Lou's is uhhh, it's just okay. Call me #StephenGlansburg, but I'm prepared to eat my yogurt alone on this one if I have to. Every devout Lou's fan treats this pizza in an Oreo-like fashion, everyone seems to have their own  special way to eat it. "Order it uncut." "Ask for the butter crust." "Dip it in their salad dressing 👯." Upon my roommates suggestion, the pizza was ordered uncut last night, so it wouldn't get soggy...Of course, it came soggy and ate like a pancake. I can't argue the popularity of this pizza, but I'll just never understand it. HOWEVER, and I'm happy to say it, the sausage was the tastiest sausage I have ever had on a pizza. Props to that. #pizza #pizzaman #chicago #chicagopizza #deepdish #chicagofoodauthority #EEEEEATS #chicagoeats

node.text: This is the best thin crust pizza I've had in Chicago, or at least a close second to Nick and Vito's (Lincoln Park is way closer than the South Side). The cracker crust is seriously thin and crispy and it travels well without getting soggy. Even though it's so thin, it's still a filling za because they don't skim on the tops. node.text: Impromptu post-work pizza party at Pequods #onatuesday. The Morton Grove location proved to be just as spot on as the restaurant in Lincoln Park. This deep dish za is a force in the Chicago pizza game and demands the respect of any casual pizza fan. It is an event. It is a heavy pizza. Nobody has ever said "let's go to Pequods and then we'll go out." No. Pequods is your night out. You don't do anything after Pequods. Respect it for what it is. #pizza #pizzaman #chicago #chicagopizza #chicagofoodauthority #chicagoeats #chicagofood #foodporn #eeeeats

A few weeks back, The Pizzaman ventured out and tried Pizanos for the first time. If you scroll down you'll find a #notsoraven review of an unimpressive deep dish za. I got a lot of heat and was told it was a #rookiemove to get Pizanos deep over Pizanos thin. The Pizza Man is not a closed minded individual and THUS, he gave it a second chance last night. Here we go. The thin crust at Pizanos tastes like a stick of butter. It's crunchy and flaky and #wheresthesauce? I prefer a chewy crust with tangy red sauce. It's not a bad pizza, it's just not a pizza to get excited about. However, I did enjoy my chicken finger and mozz stick apps. #strongappetizergame #pizza #pizzaman #chicago #chicagoeats #chicagofoodauthority #chicagofood #food #foodporn #eeeeats
